Good. Now execute the Ceph commands from the mgr pod.

Use:

oc -n openshift-storage exec -it rook-ceph-mgr-a-bc65b6668-wr2l6 -- ceph -s

Then:

oc -n openshift-storage exec -it rook-ceph-mgr-a-bc65b6668-wr2l6 -- ceph health detail

And:

oc -n openshift-storage exec -it rook-ceph-mgr-a-bc65b6668-wr2l6 -- ceph fs status

These outputs are now the most important remaining evidence.

What to specifically look for

In ceph -s:

HEALTH_WARN

slow ops

degraded PGs

recovery/backfill

nearfull/full


In ceph health detail:

MDS_SLOW_REQUEST

MDS_CLIENT_RECALL

MDS_HEALTH_CLIENT_LATE_RELEASE

slow metadata IOs

slow ops


In ceph fs status:

MDS request queue buildup

high client count

laggy MDS

replay state

cache pressure


If you see any MDS slow request or slow ops warnings, that will almost completely confirm:

> CephFS metadata latency causing temporary CMP/DMP disk-access-fail alarms.
